Dataset Builder

Greg Macfarlane

1/20/2020

This document provides a place for data manipulation and notes necessary to construct the PopulationSim implementation in the WFRC model region.

Geographic Cross-walk

PopulationSim allows to have controls at any definition provided in a crosswalk called data/geo_cross_walk.csv. We want to have controls at the following levels:

  • block group
  • tract
  • PUMA

In addition to this, we need to include the TAZ on the synthetic population so we can apply the skims in ActivitySim. To build this file, we will do the following:

  • Begin with the TAZ shapefile
  • Collect a list of block groups population centroids from the Census TIGER database
  • Determine which TAZ each block group centroid is located in.
  • If there are TAZ that do not contain a block group centroid, we will divide the blocks spatially and remap.

To make this file, we start with the TAZ Shapefile included in the WFRC _Inputs folder (previously exported to .geojson for space and simplicity)

(taz <- st_read("inputs/taz.geojson") %>% 
   # remove external stations
   filter(CO_FIPS > 0)  %>%
   # TODO: remove filter to provo/orem
   filter(TAZID > 2200, TAZID < 2500) %>%
   # only keep TAZID and county
   transmute(TAZID, CO_FIPS = sprintf("%03d", CO_FIPS), ST_FIPS = "49", 
             taz_area = st_area(.))
)

Now, we want to get a list of the population-weighted centroid for each block group.

bg_centroids <- read_csv(
  "https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/reference/cenpop2010/blkgrp/CenPop2010_Mean_BG49.txt",
  col_types = list(STATEFP = col_character(), BLKGRPCE = col_character())
) %>%
  # filter to TAZ region
  filter(COUNTYFP %in% taz$CO_FIPS) %>%
  transmute(GEOID = str_c(STATEFP, COUNTYFP, TRACTCE, BLKGRPCE), LATITUDE, LONGITUDE) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("LONGITUDE", "LATITUDE"), crs = 4326)

The map below suggests that will need some kind of control at the TAZ level. The only one we have available to us is the number of households, but that’s probably okay.

leaflet() %>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$Esri.WorldGrayCanvas) %>%
  addPolygons(data = taz, group = "TAZ", color = "red") %>%
  addCircleMarkers(data = bg_centroids, group = "bg") %>%
  addLayersControl(overlayGroups = c("BG", "TAZ"))

As a result, we need to calculate the spatial intersection of the TAZ and Block Groups layers. This generates many sliver polygons, which we remove by simply asserting that an area has to have an area larger than 500 square meters. Beyond this, we check that all TAZ are represented.

bg <- block_groups("UT", county = unique(taz$CO_FIPS), class = "sf") %>%
  st_transform(4326) %>%
  transmute(GEOID, bg_area = st_area(.))

# This generates lots of sliver and point and line intersections
cw_bg <- st_intersection(taz, bg) 
## Warning: attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant
## throughout all geometries
# so we filter out all of the points and linestrings
cw_polygons  <- cw_bg %>% filter(st_is(., "POLYGON"))
cw_mpolygons <- cw_bg %>% filter(st_is(., "MULTIPOLYGON"))
cw_geomcolls <- cw_bg %>% filter(st_is(., "GEOMETRYCOLLECTION")) %>%
  st_cast(.) %>% filter(st_is(., "POLYGON"))
## Error in st_cast_sfc_default(x): list item(s) not of class sfg
# Add them back into a single dataframe, remove areas less than 500 m2
# TODO: when we add full region, put the geomcolls back in.
cw_bg_clean <- rbind(cw_polygons, cw_mpolygons) %>%
  mutate(intersect_area = as.numeric(st_area(.))) %>%
  filter(intersect_area > 500)

The resulting intersection file is pretty complex; we’ve gone from 299 TAZs to 444 objects in the crosswalk, but that will be fine for now.

leaflet(cw_bg_clean) %>%
  addProviderTiles(providers$Esri.WorldGrayCanvas) %>%
  addPolygons()

There may be opportunities to refine this process further, but we’ll go with it for now. Let’s append the tract / PUMA lookup from the Census bureau

  transmute(TRACT = str_c(STATEFP, COUNTYFP, TRACTCE), PUMA = PUMA5CE)

Controls

Attributes we want to control for include: - Number of households - Household size - Household income - Age of persons - Household workers - Person worker status

TAZ-level controls

The only TAZ-level control we get from WFRC is the number of households in each TAZ. Therefore, this will be the only control in this file. The MAG data is only available for 2020, so that’s what we will be using even if 2017 or 2018 might be more appropriate.

tcf <- str_c("inputs/", dir("inputs/"))
taz_control <- lapply(tcf[grepl("SE_", tcf)], function(csv) {
  read_csv(csv) %>% select(TAZ = TAZID, HHBASE = TOTHH)
}) %>%
  bind_rows() %>%
  filter(TAZ %in% crosswalk$TAZ)
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   .default = col_double(),
##   CO_NAME = col_character()
## )
## See spec(...) for full column specifications.
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   .default = col_double(),
##   CO_NAME = col_character()
## )
## See spec(...) for full column specifications.
write_csv(taz_control, "data/control_totals_taz.csv")

Tract-Level Controls

The attributes available from the ACS include the following: - Household size, derived from Table B08202: HOUSEHOLD SIZE BY NUMBER OF WORKERS IN HOUSEHOLD - Household workers, derived from the same table - Age, derived from Table B01001: SEX BY AGE - Income, derived from Table B19001:HOUSEHOLD INCOME IN THE PAST 12 MONTHS (IN 2018 INFLATION-ADJUSTED DOLLARS)

First, we can collect a unique list of all the tracts we want to get controls for, alongside a complete list of all ACS variables

mytracts <- unique(crosswalk$TRACT)
mycounties <- unique(substr(crosswalk$COUNTY, 3, 5))
acsvars <- load_variables(2018, "acs5", cache = TRUE)

Household size and workers

Because these two values come in the same table, we will build them together.

swvars <- str_c("B08202_", sprintf("%03d", c(2:5, 6, 9, 13, 18)))
raw_sw <- get_acs("tract", variables = swvars, state = "UT", county = mycounties)
## Getting data from the 2013-2017 5-year ACS
size_work <- raw_sw %>% 
  left_join(acsvars, by = c("variable" = "name")) %>%
  separate(label, c("VAR", "total", "label"), sep = "!!") %>%
  select(GEOID, label, estimate) 

works <- size_work %>%
  filter(grepl("work", label)) %>%
  mutate(
    num_work = str_extract(label, "\\d+"),
    workcat = case_when(
      num_work == 1 ~ "HHWORK1",
      num_work == 2 ~ "HHWORK2",
      num_work == 3 ~ "HHWORK3",
      TRUE ~ "HHWORK0"
    )
  ) %>% 
  group_by(GEOID, workcat) %>% summarize(count = sum(estimate))

sizes <- size_work %>%
  filter(!grepl("work", label)) %>%
  mutate(
   num_size = str_extract(label, "\\d+"),
   sizecat = str_c("HHSIZE", num_size) 
  ) %>%
  group_by(GEOID, sizecat) %>% summarize(count = sum(estimate))

Age

First we get the number of people of each age category.

agevars <- str_c("B01001_", sprintf("%03d", c(3:25, 27:49)))
raw_ages <- get_acs("tract", variables = agevars, state = "UT", county = mycounties)
## Getting data from the 2013-2017 5-year ACS
ages <- raw_ages %>%
  left_join(acsvars, by = c("variable" = "name")) %>%
  separate(label, c("VAR", "total", "sex", "age"), sep = "!!") %>%
  select(GEOID, sex, age, estimate)  %>%
  
  # regroup age categories
  mutate(
    numage = as.numeric(substr(age, 1, 2)),
    agecat = case_when(
      numage %in% c(15:24) ~ "PAGE1",
      numage %in% c(25:54) ~ "PAGE2",
      numage %in% c(55:64) ~ "PAGE3",
      numage %in% c(65:99) ~ "PAGE4",
      TRUE ~ "PAGE0" # children less than 15 not categorized in demo
    )
  ) %>%
  
  # consolidate men and women
  group_by(GEOID, agecat) %>%
  summarise(count = sum(estimate))
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion

Income

incvars <- str_c("B19001_", sprintf("%03d", c(2:17)))
raw_incs <- get_acs("tract", variables = incvars, state = "UT", county = mycounties)
## Getting data from the 2013-2017 5-year ACS
incs <- raw_incs %>%
  left_join(acsvars, by = c("variable" = "name")) %>%
  separate(label, c("VAR", "total", "income"), sep = "!!") %>%
  select(GEOID, income, estimate)  %>%
  # regroup income categories
  mutate(
    numinc  = stringr::str_extract(income, "\\d+"),
    inccat = case_when(
      numinc <  15 ~ "HHINC1",
      numinc <  30 ~ "HHINC2",
      numinc <  60 ~ "HHINC3",
      numinc >= 60 ~ "HHINC4",
      TRUE ~ as.character(NA)
    )
  ) %>%
  group_by(GEOID, inccat) %>%
  summarise(count = sum(estimate))

Number of Households

We will put the number of households at the tract on the controls data frame, but we will not use it at this point.

raw_hh <- get_acs("tract", variables = "B08202_001", state = "UT", county = mycounties)
## Getting data from the 2013-2017 5-year ACS
hh <- raw_hh %>%
  select(GEOID, HHBASE = estimate)

Tract Controls File

Now, we write out the tract controls file.

(tract_controls <- tibble(TRACT = mytracts) %>%
   left_join(ages  %>% spread(agecat,  count), by = c("TRACT" = "GEOID")) %>%
   left_join(incs  %>% spread(inccat,  count), by = c("TRACT" = "GEOID")) %>%
   left_join(works %>% spread(workcat, count), by = c("TRACT" = "GEOID")) %>%
   left_join(sizes %>% spread(sizecat, count), by = c("TRACT" = "GEOID")) %>% 
   left_join(hh, by = c("TRACT" = "GEOID")) 
)

PUMS Seed Data

The uncompressed seed data is too large to commit, so we have committed compressed versions of the original files. We need to clean and re-save the PUMS seed data files for households and for people. In the case of households, this entails filtering the households without people, and replacing NA values in the controls with other values.

# read in pums HH file, specifying datatypes for key columns
pums_hh <- read_csv(
  "inputs/psam_h49.csv.zip",  
  col_types = list(SERIALNO = col_character(), NP = col_integer(), 
                   FINCP = col_number(), ADJINC = col_number(),
                   WGTP = col_number())
)

#' A function to replace NA values with non-missing stupid numbers
replace_na <- function(x) {
  ifelse(is.na(x),-8,x)
}

seed_hh <- pums_hh %>%
  # remove empty households
  filter(NP > 0) %>%
  mutate(
    # create unique hh_id field
    hh_id = 1:nrow(.),
    # compute adjusted numeric income
    HHINCADJ = FINCP * ADJINC
  ) %>%
  # apply replacement function to key variables
  mutate_at(.vars = vars(NP, WIF, WGTP, HHINCADJ), replace_na)
pums_persons <- read_csv(
  "inputs/psam_p49.csv.zip", 
  col_types = list(SERIALNO = col_character(), PWGTP = col_number())
)

seed_per <- pums_persons %>%
  # join hhid field
  left_join(seed_hh %>% select(SERIALNO, hh_id)) %>%
  # replace NA values with something less stupid
  mutate_at(.vars = vars(PWGTP, AGEP), replace_na)

Remove NA fields from seed files

Replace NA fields with a negative integer to avoid errors and write to disk.

seed_hh %>%
  mutate_all(replace_na) %>% 
  write_csv("data/seed_households.csv")

seed_per %>%
  mutate_all(replace_na) %>% 
  write_csv("data/seed_persons.csv")

Meta Controls

PopulationSim requires (we think) at least some region-level controls. We will simply sum up the total households in the controls data to work with this.

(meta <- tract_controls %>%
  summarise(REGION = 1,
            totalPOP = sum(PAGE0) +  sum(PAGE1) +  sum(PAGE2) +  sum(PAGE3) +  sum(PAGE4)))
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   REGION totalPOP
##    <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1      1   287236
write_csv(meta, "data/control_totals_meta.csv")
